entity.name: Isak Dinesen
entity.text: Isak Dinesen (DEE-nuh-suhn), born Karen Christenze Dinesen, is Denmark’s most prominent twentieth century author and one of the most distinctive voices in modern Western literature. She was born in a suburb of Copenhagen in 1885, the daughter of Wilhelm Dinesen, an army officer, landowner, wanderer, and storyteller, and Ingeborg Westenholz, a matriarch in the staunchest Victorian tradition. It was from her father that Dinesen inherited the restlessness that motivated her to escape to Africa and [...] Isak Dinesen, born Karen Christenze Dinesen in 1885 in Denmark, is recognized as one of the most prominent authors of the twentieth century and a distinctive voice in modern Western literature. Her early years were marked by a struggle against the constraints of her bourgeois upbringing, leading her to Kenya, where she married her cousin and managed a coffee plantation from 1914 to 1931. This period in Africa became a significant influence on her writing, despite the challenges she faced, [...] Thurman, Judith. Isak Dinesen: The Life of a Storyteller. New York: St. Martin’s Press, 1982. Thurman’s biography constitutes the fullest treatment of Dinesen’s life and work in any language. Meticulously researched and highly readable, it provides an account of the writer’s life, brief analyses of her works, and extensive discussion of the relationship between her life and works. Addressed to both scholars and an educated nonspecialist audience, it contains scholarly notes, a select

Designation: Storyteller of Africa - Gothic Romantic of Fate
Bio: Isak Dinesen (Karen Blixen, 1885-1962), Danish author best known for 'Out of Africa' and 'Babette's Feast.' Lived in Kenya running a coffee plantation from 1914-1931, an experience that profoundly shaped her writing. Master of the gothic tale and romantic storytelling, she wrote with aristocratic elegance about fate, loss, art, and the clash between European and African worldviews.
